NORMALISED EXTRACT
Definition
The Hamming distance between two equal-length sequences (strings, vectors, or bit-strings) is the count of positions at which the corresponding symbols differ.
Formula
Given two sequences a and b of length n: distance = sum_{i=0..n-1} [a_i != b_i]
Unicode-aware string semantics
When applied to strings, comparisons must be performed on Unicode code points, not UTF-16 code units. Use a code-point iterator (for...of, Array.from, or manual codePointAt handling) to ensure surrogate pairs are treated as a single item.
Bit-level semantics
For non-negative integers, compute XOR (x ^ y) then count set bits in the XOR result (popcount) to get the bit-level Hamming distance.
Algorithms and complexity
String algorithm: iterate code points once and increment counter when code points differ. Time O(n) where n is number of code points; O(1) extra space.
Bit algorithm: compute z = x XOR y, then compute popcount(z). Typical popcount implementations:
- Kernighan: while z != 0 do z = z & (z-1); count++ -> O(k) where k is number of set bits.
- Table lookup: split into bytes and sum precomputed 256-entry table -> O(w/8) for w-bit words.
- SWAR/parallel bit-count for fixed widths (implementation-specific) -> constant-time arithmetic operations.
Edge cases and validation
- String inputs: must be equal in code point length for string Hamming distance; otherwise throw TypeError or return defined error.
- Bit inputs: accept Number (treated as 32-bit unsigned/signed depending on context) or BigInt; when using BigInt, convert both operands to BigInt prior to XOR.
- Type mixing (Number vs BigInt) must be normalized explicitly; in JS mixing throws TypeError.
