DETAILS
1. Definition and formula
  - distance = count of differing positions.
2. Unicode handling (strings)
  - Use String iterator (for...of) or manual surrogate-pair combining using codePointAt to read full code points.
  - Do not rely on .length for code point counts; .length reports UTF-16 code units.
3. Bitwise method (integers)
  - Compute XOR: z = a XOR b
  - Compute popcount(z) using one of the popcount methods (Kernighan, table lookup, SWAR).
4. Algorithms and complexity
  - String: single-pass code point comparison, O(n).
  - Bitwise: XOR cost + popcount cost; popcount complexity depends on algorithm chosen.
5. Edge cases and validation
  - If inputs are not valid types or sizes, return or throw a TypeError.
REFERENCE DETAILS
API signatures (recommended patterns)
- hammingDistanceStrings(a: string, b: string) -> number
  Parameters: a and b are strings. Function must iterate code points and return integer distance. Throws TypeError if code point counts differ or inputs not strings.
- hammingDistanceBits(a: number|BigInt, b: number|BigInt) -> number
  Parameters: a and b are integers. Convert both to the same integer type (prefer BigInt for arbitrary precision); compute z = a ^ b; return popcount(z) as Number.
IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
- For JS, prefer BigInt when working with integers outside the 32-bit domain: BigInt(a) ^ BigInt(b) -> BigInt; compute popcount with Kernighan using BigInt-friendly loop.
- For strings, use for (const cp of string) { ... } to iterate code points.
SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Use Intl.Segmenter when grapheme-cluster (user-perceived character) comparisons are required; Hamming distance normally compares code points.
- When implementing in typed languages, document the bit-width used for integer inputs and whether leading zeros are considered in bit-distance calculations.
